,Recommended,262940,19487528,"Posted: 4 December, 2015",all,fathergwyneth,"Back by nostalgic demand, this fifth installment of the franchise is something of a return to form, albeit one that is as guilty of replicating the faults of previous games as it at revisiting the strengths.Abandoning the 3D worlds and returning to a 2D style, reminiscent of the first two installements, helps the game recapture the appealing artwork style that enhanced the atmosphere of those first two adventures. Not to mention the return of Barrington Pheloung on soundtrack duties. Meanwhile voice work is largely of a good quality, spear-headed by Rolf Saxon's now iconic performance as George Stobbart.However, it's the story that really starts to let things down, with the plot taking some silly turns that push the player out of the narrative, keeping you at arm's length from really engaging with the events unfolding on screen. There are also a handful of puzzles that are frustrating in a way that stops you feeling like you're really experiencing the thoughtful adventure, meaning that you spend ages pursuing an idea that seems right, receive no confirmation that you're making any progress, and then feel lost, only to realise that you were right to begin with... and not in some sort of rewarding ""I'm a genius!"" fashion, sadly.It also feels terribly anti-climatic, though that's been a problem of every single Broken Sword game, but, for fans of this series, this is a much appreciated step back in the right direction, and undoubtedly the third best game in the series, though that's both high praise and something of a back-handed compliment."
76561198089052394,Recommended,262940,30999270,Posted: 7 April,all,JD Herrera,"Broken Sword 5 - The Serpent's Curse			* 8/10The latest (not the last, I heard they're working on a new BS) chapter of this saga comes back with a classic yet renewed style!After the questionable 3d and keyboard input experiments with the 3rd and 4th chapters, this 5th chapter presents itself in a classic aspect, the way we used to know Broken Sword as in its most appreciated chapters (1st and 2nd). 2d characters (actually 3d, but then exported in 2d) on 2d beatifully drawn ambiences.As usual the story starts very quickly: George and Nico meet up by chance for work reasons at an art gallery in Paris and they both witness the homicide of the gallery owner and the theft of a particular painting, which is the core of this story as the entire adventure revolves around it. Obviously this time the purpose will be to find the killer, who's behind him and what is the story behind that particular painting.The spirit of the game is back at its origin, we'll see new characters but also old acquaintances (a special mention for the Goat), the game can be played with just the mouse again and the interface is very intuitive.We'll be visiting many locations and almost all of them are well realized, with details, or great sceneries or good old humour (special mention for Pugs), which is always present in George's speech.Dialogues are always important, they reveal informations and even though they're not always essential they give shape to characters (special mention for the ""gardener"" with Nico).Riddles sometimes can be hard to understand or solve (special mention for the ""sancuary"" and the dark cave) but there's nothing that can be impossible if you try to understand all the elements around you and try with logic and George's logic, according to the situation.The story is very pleasant to follow, a thrilling starting point, hideous characters, old acquaintances, many plot twists and revelations, everything with a touch of classic humour in the right points.To make it short this chapter is another one of my favourites among the frist two chapters. Good job Revolution, I can't wait for the next chapter!+++PROs+++IT'S BROKEN SWORD!A chapter realized with the successful recipe that made the first two titles so good is not a guarantee for success, but it makes a good title if you add it a good story, easter eggs and a good soundtrack.---CONs---DIFFICULTIES.I have to admit I had some trouble with few riddles, especially in the final part of the game.I played this game on this machine:Intel Core i7-497016Gb RAM DDR3GeForce GTX 660Windows 10 Professional x64"
,Recommended,262940,33037129,Posted: 30 June,all,One Lemonade,"TL;DRIt's amazing. All point-and-click or Broken Sword fans should buy it.10/10In-depth reviewWhether you're new to the Broken Sword franchise or a fan of the previous games, this game is a must play for all point-and-click fans. The beautiful sceneries, the head scratching puzzles and the gripping storyline make this my favourite Broken Sword so far.PuzzlesThe puzzles in Broken Sword 5 are, one word; fantastic. The difficulty of them are perfect, as no puzzle can be solved instantly, and no puzzle will make you pull your hair out and bring up a guide. They are all relative, and once solved allow the player to progress further into the game.10/10GraphicsThe game is designed in a cartoon fashion, but that doesn't stop it looking brilliant. The scenery and art work that got put into this game is phenomenal and it is truly easy to appreciate the time and effort that went into it. Who doesn't like a beautiful background while solving puzzles?10/10GameplayBe aware it is a point and click game! But as far as point and clicks go, the gameplay is truly on point. Theonlysmall negative I can make about the entire game is here, and it's that it can be a little slow in places. There was a point or two where I was like""Oh just hurry up!"", but it was a very rare occurrence (but for those of you who are wanting a relaxing experience - it's perfect!). The storyline is terrific and encourages you to continue playing as you cannot wait to find out more.9/10StorylineSpoilers, obviously!The story starts off as good old George Stobbart in Paris, typically in an art gallery. A famous (or so-called infamous by a local priest) as arrived at the gallery, and the owner Henri is excited about showing it off. All is not as it seems, as a robbery takes places and the owner of the gallery gets in the way of a bullet. Clever George is not convinced that this was a normal robbery and believes it's a inside job, so who else to figure this case out that George Stobbart and the beautiful Nico Collard.Travelling around Europe, the duo attempt to find the real reason behind the robbery and the truth regarding theinfamouspainting, La Maledicció. After getting involved with bad people, they soon realise that there is a lot more to this robbery that George first thought. Several people are claiming ownership to the painting, and different meaning behind the painting are being discussed. The duo sets out to meet these people claiming ownership and to discover the powers the painting possesses. Will they figure out what is so strange about the painting?10/10Final VerdictWith an excellent storyline, beautiful graphics style and awesome gameplay, I highly recommend this game. There are also achievements and trading cards to help tempt you that little bit more.OVERALL: 10/10"
