,Recommended,262940,7927837,"Posted: 5 December, 2013",all,MazLad,"Really enjoying it so far but it's difficult to account for how much this is influenced by Nostalgia.It has a very similar feeling to the first two Broken Sword games, both in style and content. It's evident a bit of care has gone into the storyline and I'm keen to see if they keep the quality up through both episodes.As this is quite a nostalgic game, it will feel quite dated, particularly to those who have't invested in the series previously. Unlike current games it's very much on rails and doesn't include faux interactivity though moral choices, not that this is necessarily a bad thing. It's very much a straightforward puzzle point and click adventure game.I'd certainly recommend the game to would be buyers, but would advise new people to the franchise to try to get hold of the original Broken Sword and give it a play through. I went back to it recently and it has some very clever puzzles of the right kind of difficulty, almost a more logical Monkey Island, (which I also enjoy of course!)Perhaps look for the original version if you can, as the Director's Cut has had a very mixed reception).This new game comes into an time where there's more of a walkthrough culture in games where there can be a focus on 100%ing, getting all achievements and all that jazz. I'd really recommend bucking this trend for this game to just jump in and work through it at your own pace."
