,Recommended,262940,8616423,"Posted: 8 January, 2014",all,johnbenston,"Part 2 is now out so I am recreating my review of the game.The game is a point and click adventure like the first two games so do not be fooled by the name ""Broken Sword"" there is nothing involving slaying monsters.  To those of you who have not played any Broken Sword games I would recommend you play the first two or three that are also available here on steam, although not required the game makes references and jokes that refer to previous games and will make the overall game much more enjoyable.For those of you who worry about the game being of the same quality as the fourth installment do not let that alone stop you from buying the game.  Broken Sword 5 does a wonderful job of mixing the classic 2d elements of the first two games and bringing in fresh new models for characters.  The game also goes back to the roots with its dialogue, the game is nicely written with excellent full voice acting.  Although not my favorite soundtrack for Broken Sword games all the fresh soundtracks are still solid, and I was excited to see a few of the soundtracks were recycled.  They even have an option for the option between new or old style dialogue bubbles, they successfully made a game that uses fresh ideas and still has that classic feel to it.  For those of you who are fans the game in many cases lives up and brings back the classic gameplay which has been missed for so long.Although I loved the game I do have a few things I was dissapointed in.  I felt like although the game was very well written that it wasn't as well written as the first two games, maybe that is me just having a bias towards the first two games.  The game has many references to the previous installments, though I admit a lot were pretty funny sometimes there were just to many references so close to each other that it kind of took the feel that it was its own game away at times.  Some of the puzzles did not live up to my expectations.  The game for me was easier than the previous games but that was not my real problem, my problem was that some of the puzzles would involve luck if attempted in real life, I do not want to spoil anything so I will not use an example but it in a way took away from the game for me.  Most of the characters were very enjoyable but I did not like Inspector Navet, I thought he was just a silly character that just did not seem to fit in the series in my oppinion.  Lastly I would have liked to see an option to use classic style characters, although I enjoyed the new character designs it would have been nice to see the old style, yes I understand it would be hard and yes I know it would take more space I am just being honest on what I would like to have seen.  I really enjoyed this game and if you went through all of my review you noticed that my complaints were pretty minor as I didn't find anything really fundamentally wrong with the game and had to dig pretty deep to find negatives but most of them are from comparisons to the previous games instead of the game as a stand alone.8/10"
