,Not Recommended,262940,15320019,"Posted: 12 April, 2015",all,HausMaus,"I will preface this review by saying that Broken Sword 2 was the first video game I ever played when I got my first PC about 17 years ago. It left a huge imprint on my gamer psyche and made me an avid fan of point and click adventures. After finishing The Smoking Mirror, I went to the original installment and my mind was blown - it was even better. The old games didn't have the best graphics in the modern sense, but their world felt rich, alive and intricate. Every character felt real, tangible and memorable. I never felt as though I was only playing a video game - it felt like an entire new world, with its own characters, stakeholders and conspiracies. Every location was a treat and seemed alive and genuine.Sadly, not many of these things can be said for The Serpent's Curse. The game attempts to cater to the original fanbase by doing a lot of fan service, such as reintroducing certain characters and puzzles from the previous games, but it fails miserably at evoking the feelings of The Shadow of the Templars and The Smoking Mirror. The few locations that are introduced feel bland, static, unalive and uninteresting. The characters are even more boring and lifeless. The game attempts to buy cheap points by taking us to familiar locations such an art gallery in Paris and an old mansion in Spain, and this particular manipulation is obvious from the very beginning. The whole world of BS 5 feels static and fake. Sure the graphics are nice, but that's not enough to offset the constant feeling of emptiness and as though the game was rushed in order to maximize its profit margin. The ending is particularly bland and disappointing, and it's hard to imagine that such poor writing actually made it into the game.Whether I recommend playing The Serpent's Curse or not depends on what you're looking for. If you want to relive the experience and memories of the old games, give this one a wide berth. If you're simply looking for a somewhat decent pont and click adventure, it might be worth a playthrough... but keep your expectations in check."
,Recommended,262940,20470947,"Posted: 11 January, 2016",all,Mellow_Online1,"I was so happy that one of my favourite point and click franchises was getting a new game, 7 years after the last game was released. I was jumping with excitement. What did I think of it when it came out? It was good..... That's basically all I can say about it. I really wanted to say more about this because I was expecting more, especially after a hugely successful kickstarter campaign making more than double the original target. I loved all of the broken sword games, I even have a disagreement with how people treat the 4th game. But it just seems to be missing the charm the other games had, the same goes for BS4. Whereabouts does this game rank along with the broken sword games, it ranks 4th. It's better than 4 but not as good as 2,3 or 1.My one gripe I have with this are the puzzles seem way too simple and straight forward. Same thing as the director's cut of the original. They dumb down the puzzles so that people with half a brain could do. You just need to do the basic adventure things in order to do the puzzles. It doesn't really do much to stand out from the crowd. They also have the hint system make a return from 1 and 2, but unlike them, the hint system seems unnecessary. Again because of the simple puzzles.The artwork is beautiful, as usual for broken sword. But the artwork in this seems better than the other games, especially the dated graphics of 3 and 4. Movements seem crisp and smooth which is a huge improvement of the awkward movements of NPCs in 1 and 2.Dialogue is basically the same as the previous games so not much to talk about there.Characters are again your typical broken sword characters. So not much to talk about there.I think a few of the critics are missing the point of this game as well as other point click games. They're saying that it's timeless. Any point and click game can be timeless as long as it's done right. Point and click games are similar to old Atari 2600 games and nes game. They're so simple by today's standards but if they're done correct they can leave an impact on the gaming community as a whole. Easy to make but hard to master.I love the idea of resurrecting old franchises as it appealsto all sorts of gamers. Newer gamers grab it because it looks new and interesting and older gamers grab it for the nostalgia. That's why I just love the feeling of playing another Broken Sword game and it was a good experience. Now I just need to wait for the next Monkey Island.Steam Curator group:http://steamcommunity.com/groups/MellowReviews"
